Abstract

System Architecture

We manually gathered a claimed set of ~174 student resumes

by name from the IIITD Anuj Grover list, parsed them into

structured JSON, stored the rich profiles in MongoDB, and

mirrored the relationships into Neo4j so we can answer

natural-language talent queries with precision. A multi-stage

pipeline uses local, laptop-feasible Qwen models to translate

user intent into Cypher and to generate embeddings for

semantic recall. At query time, we combine exact graph

filtering with vector similarity and rank results using a

transparent, multi-factor scoring model. The goal is to let

recruiters or faculty ask for “top ML/DL candidates with

startup experience and CGPA ≥ 8” and get a fast,

explainable, ranked list — without cloud dependencies or

API quotas.

Model and Scoring

Multi-Stage Query Processing

We use Qwen-2-7B-Instruct (4-bit) for classification, intent

extraction, and Cypher drafting, and Qwen-2-7B-Embedding

(4-bit) for generating skills, domain, and student vectors. Both

models run locally to avoid quotas and protect PII. Candidate

ranking uses a weighted scoring model with the following claimed

defaults: Domain (40%), Skill (25%), Experience (20%), Academic

(10%), and Contextual (5%). Each result includes an explanation,

enabling users to see why a candidate ranks highly, such as

domain match strength, CGPA relevance, or alignment with prior

work experience.

Conclusion & Future Work

Hybrid Search

Hybrid search (Cypher + vectors): Cypher ensures precise filtering, while

vectors provide semantic recall (e.g., “AI” → ML/DL/CV). Results are merged

and re-ranked to balance precision and recall, avoiding the latency and noise

of RAG/GraphRAG while keeping rankings explainable.

Workflow (Multi-Stage Query Processing)

● 3) Dual execution:

● 1) Classification: Detect whether the query is skill-led, domain-led, hybrid, or filter-driven.

● 2) Intent extraction & decomposition: Extract skills, domains, filters, and assign weights to atomic components.

○ Generate Cypher from intent and run it on Neo4j for exact matches.

○ In parallel, embed the query and run vector similarity against stored profile/domain/skill embeddings.

● 4) Merge & refine: Merge and deduplicate Cypher and vector results; relax constraints if sparse or tighten if dense.

● 5) Scoring & ranking: Apply the multi-factor scoring model with explanations, then return top ranked candidates.

